\layout Title

A series representation for the Riemann Zeta derived from the Gauss-Kuzmin-Wirsi
ng Operator
\layout Author

Linas Vepstas <linas@linas.org>
\layout Date

2 January 2004 (revised 29 August 2005)
\layout Abstract

A series representation for the Riemann zeta function in terms of the falling
 Pochhammer symbol is derived from the polynomial representation of the
 Gauss-Kuzmin-Wirsing (GKW) operator.
 
\layout Section

Introduction
\layout Standard

The Gauss-Kuzmin-Wirsing operator 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Kuzmin,Wirsing,Babenko}

\end_inset 

 occurs in the theory of continued fraction representations of the real
 numbers.
 The zeroth eigenvalue of this operator is related to the Gauss-Kuzmin distribut
ion [ref], giving the likelihood of the occurrence of an integer in the
 continued-fraction expansion of an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

arbitrary
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 real number.
 The GKW operator is interesting in other ways, notably in its relationship
 to the Minkowski Question Mark function, and thus its symmetry under the
 action of a monoid sub-semi-group of the modular group 
\begin_inset Formula $SL(2,\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset 

.
 Except for the zeroth eigenvector, there is no known closed-form solution
 of the GKW operator, although the eigenvalues may be computed relatively
 easily through standard matrix diagonalization techniques.
\layout Standard

In this paper, a relationship to the Riemann zeta function 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Edwards}

\end_inset 

 is noted, allowing the easy derivation of a series expansion of the zeta
 function in terms of the Pochhammer symbols (the falling factorials), or
 equivalently the binomial coefficients.
 Specifically, the expansion given is
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta(s)=\frac{s}{s-1}-s\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}(-)^{n}\left(\begin{array}{c}
s-1\\
n\end{array}\right)t_{n}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

Here, the constants 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset 

 play a role analogous to the Stieltjes constants, and can be given in a
 simple, finite-term closed form, involving the Riemann zeta function at
 integer values and the Euler-Mascheroni constant.
 
\layout Standard

The 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset 

 may be used to express the Stieltjes constants as a sum involving the Stirling
 numbers.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset 

 are very well behaved, becoming small quite rapidly.
 Some exact expressions can be derived for various sums involving these
 constants.
 A numerical exploration of their values is also performed, from which the
 limiting behavior is conjectured.
\layout Standard

The first section defines the GKW operator in simple terms, as the transfer
 operator of the Gauss map.
 The second section briefly reviews some of the properties of the GKW operator,
 and the third section provides several polynomial representations.
 The fourth section obtains the series expansion for the zeta.
 The fifth section explores the values of the constants 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Section

The Gauss-Kuzmin-Wirsing Operator
\layout Standard

Successive terms of a continued fraction fraction expansion for a real number
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 may be obtained by iterating on the function 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
h(x)=\frac{1}{x}-\left\lfloor \frac{1}{x}\right\rfloor \label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 This function maps the unit interval onto itself, and is sometimes called
 the Gauss map.
 It is connected to the Riemann zeta function by a Mellin transform:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta(s)=\frac{1}{s-1}-s\int_{0}^{1}h(x)\, x^{s-1}dx\label{eq:zeta-as-gauss-map}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

In the theory of iterated functions, the behavior of a map may be studied
 by means of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

transfer operator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

, sometimes called the Frobenius-Perron operator of a map 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Ruelle}

\end_inset 

.
 Given a map of the unit interval onto itself, the transfer operator describes
 how a distribution on the unit interval behaves under the action of the
 map, thus giving an broader view of iteration.
 In particular, the transfer operator can act as a bridge between the fractal
 properties typically seen when iterating a function, and analytic descriptions
 of the same process.
 This is because transfer operators can be represented both on the space
 of smooth, differentiable functions, as well as spaces of non-differentiable
 functions.
\layout Standard

By using a set of smooth, differentiable, orthonormal basis functions on
 the unit interval, such as orthogonal polynomials, the matrix elements
 of a transfer operator can often be explicitly computed, and the operator
 itself can be diagonalized, using standard techniques from the theory of
 Hilbert spaces and functional analysis.
 
\layout Standard

There are a variety of equivalent definitions for the transfer operator,
 of varying degrees of sophistication.
 One simple definition is 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[U_{h}\rho\right](x)=\int dy\;\delta\left(x-h(y)\right)\;\rho(y)\label{eq:Transfer as Change of Variable}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset 

 is the function being iterated, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset 

 is some density on which the transfer operator 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset 

 acts.
 The subscript on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset 

 is used to emphasize that the transfer operator is associated with the
 function being iterated.
 In this expression, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset 

 is understood to be the Dirac delta function.
 As can be seen, as iteration maps one point to another, the transfer operator
 describes how the density is mapped.
 
\layout Standard

A more abstract definition may be given.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $h:X\to X$
\end_inset 

 be a map from an arbitrary set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset 

 onto itself.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho:X\to\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset 

 be a valuation of that set on the complex numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset 

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset 

 be the space of all such valuations 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset 

.
 Then the transfer operator 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset 

 is a linear functional on the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset 

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}:\mathcal{R}\to\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset 

, acting as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[U_{h}\rho\right](x)=\sum_{y\in h^{-1}(x)}\rho(y)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Rather than studying 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset 

 acting on the whole space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}$
\end_inset 

, it is often insightful to represent 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}$
\end_inset 

 acting only on a subspace.
 For example, when 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset 

 is the unit interval, one may consider only the space of (finite) polynomials,
 or the space of analytic functions, or the space of square-integrable functions
, etc.
\layout Standard

For the Gauss map, the transfer operator is known as the Gauss-Kuzmin-Wirsing
 (GKW) operator, and has the representation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Khinchin}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[U_{h}\rho\right](x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{(n+x)^{2}}\rho\left(\frac{1}{n+x}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The definition 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Transfer as Change of Variable}

\end_inset 

 can be loosely viewed as a kind of change-of-variable.
 This change-of-variable can be performed on equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:zeta-as-gauss-map}

\end_inset 

, the order of integration exchanged, and the Gauss map replaced by its
 transfer operator.
 One obtains the operator equation
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta(s)=\frac{s}{s-1}-s\int_{0}^{1}dx\; x\left[U_{h}x^{s-1}\right]\label{eq:Zeta as operator integral}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Although the above equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Zeta as operator integral}

\end_inset 

 is easy enough to derive, a proper, rigorous examination of its validity
 requires a deep study of topics in functional analysis, topics outside
 the scope of this paper.
 Wirsing does present some arguments concerning the existence and analyticity
 of the eigenvectors of this operator; however, the arguments are specific
 to this operator and do not draw on any general theory 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Wirsing}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

This expression of the Riemann zeta function in terms of the GKW operator
 motivates a deeper study to the GKW operator, and of transfer operators
 in general.
 Most curiously, continued fractions have a variety of interesting connections
 to the modular group 
\begin_inset Formula $SL(2,\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset 

, and indeed, the modular group can be viewed as a symmetry group of the
 dyadic tree representation of the unit interval afforded by both the binary
 numbers and the Farey numbers.
 Thus, one is lead to ask if the Riemann Hypothesis (RH) can be deduced
 from a set of symmetries/invariances of 
\begin_inset Formula $SL(2,\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset 

 acting on the unit interval, and, in particular, the symmetries of operators
 that commute with the GKW operator.
 
\layout Standard

A complete analysis of the GKW operator 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Babenko}

\end_inset 

 has never been given, and appears to be difficult at many levels.
 The operator has one well-known eigenvector, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)=1/(1+x)$
\end_inset 

, called the Gauss distribution, as it was known to Gauss.
 It corresponds to the unit eigenvalue.
 A closed form for the other eigenvectors is not known.
 The next eigenvalue has the approximate value 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}\thickapprox0.3036630029...$
\end_inset 

 and is known as the Gauss-Kuzmin-Wirsing constant; it gives the rate of
 (exponential) convergence of distributions of continued fraction expansions
 to the Gauss distribution.
\layout Standard

The author has attempted a computer-guided search for a closed-form solution
 in terms of a simple linear combination of products of common special functions
, including the factorial, the digamma, and Bessel functions.
 No solution was found; it is not clear that the eigenvectors have any simple
 solution in terms of common special functions.
\layout Standard

