\layout Section

Assorted Algebraic Identities
\layout Standard

The action of the GKW operator can be computed explicitly for a variety
 of simple functions.
 This section lists an assortment of random algebraic results, none particularly
 deep, although many are suggestive in various ways.
 These are listed here mostly for the sake of completeness.
 
\layout Standard

Adjacent terms in the series can be made to cancel by shifting the series
 by one:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[U_{h}f\right](x)-\left[U_{h}f\right](x+1)=\frac{1}{(1+x)^{2}}f\left(\frac{1}{1+x}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 which holds for any function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x).$
\end_inset 

 Thus, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(x)$
\end_inset 

 is an eigenvector, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}\rho=\lambda\rho$
\end_inset 

, then it would also solve 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{1}{(1+x)^{2}}\rho\left(\frac{1}{1+x}\right)=\lambda\left(\rho(x)-\rho(x+1)\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

This can be solved easily to get the zeroth eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho_{0}(x)=\frac{1}{\ln2}\;\frac{1}{1+x}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 which satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $[U_{h}\rho_{0}](x)=\rho_{0}(x)$
\end_inset 

 and the normalization is given by requiring 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\int_{0}^{1}\rho_{0}(x)\, dx=1\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

A reflection identity is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=1-(1+x)^{-2}$
\end_inset 

 which satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}f=1-f$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

A hint of the relation to the modular group is given by simple identities
 involving the Minkowski Question Mark function 
\begin_inset Formula $?(x)$
\end_inset 

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
U_{h}[(1+?(x))/(1+x)^{2}]=1-?(x)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The Minkowski Question Mark function is an isomorphism of dyadic trees;
 specifically the binary tree that represents the real numbers as a binary
 expansion, and the Stern-Brocot or Farey tree, the binary tree that represents
 the real numbers by the rational numbers.
 In this context, its important to keep in mind that the modular group 
\begin_inset Formula $SL(2,\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset 

 is the group of symmetries or hyperbolic rotations of binary trees, and
 that the Question Mark enjoys a set of fractal self-similarities under
 the action of the modular group.
 Another question mark identity is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
U_{h}[?(x)\, x^{-2}]=2-?(x)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Additional identities may be constructed in this vein, for example: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
U_{h}\left[?(x)\left(\frac{1}{(1+x)^{2}}-2\right)\right]=\frac{?(x)-2}{(1+x)^{2}}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 but these types of exercises do not seem to lead to any sort of obviously
 worthwhile recurrence relations; a deeper analysis of symmetries is required.
 
\layout Standard

Acting on the monomial, one gets 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[U_{h}x^{s}\right](x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\,\frac{1}{(n+x)^{s+2}}=\zeta_{H}(s+2,1+x)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{H}(s,q)$
\end_inset 

 is the Hurwitz zeta function.
 For positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $s=k$
\end_inset 

, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{H}(k+1,x)=(-1)^{k+1}\psi^{(k)}(x)/k!$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi^{(k)}(x)$
\end_inset 

 is the polygamma function, the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

'th derivative of the gamma function.
 For negative integers, one gets the Bernoulli polynomials: 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{H}(-n,x)=-B_{n+1}(x)/(n+1)$
\end_inset 

.
 As a variation, one has curiosities such as 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=(1+ax)^{2}$
\end_inset 

 giving 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}f=\psi^{(1)}(1+x+a)$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=(1+nx)^{-2}-1$
\end_inset 

 giving 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}f=-\sum_{k=1}^{n}(x+k)^{-2}$
\end_inset 

 (this last being a finite sum).
\layout Standard

The relatively simple expressions involving the Hurwitz zeta and the Minkowski
 question mark function again strongly hint that the modular group is deeply
 involved in the correct theory of the GKW operator.
 For example, the Bernoulli map 
\begin_inset Formula $b(x)=2x-\left\lfloor 2x\right\rfloor $
\end_inset 

, when iterated, gives the binary digits of the real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

.
 The transfer operator of the Bernoulli map is exactly solvable: the eigenfuncti
ons are the Bernoulli polynomials, and more generally, the Hurwitz zeta
 function.
 
\layout Standard

In closing, one teasing hint of the relationship between period-doubling
 and the GKW is this curious representation of the zeroth eigenvector as
 a sum over progressively smaller intervals: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{1}{1+x}=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\,\frac{1}{2^{n}}\left[\frac{2}{x+n}-\frac{1}{x+n+1}\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Section

Polynomial Representation
\layout Standard

The search for analytic solutions to the GKW operator begins with a specificatio
n of the operator in a polynomial basis.
 To that end, a natural first choice is to consider a representation in
 terms of the monomials 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}$
\end_inset 

 or equivalently, a Taylor expansion about 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset 

.
 This proves to be an unfortunate choice, as will become clear; The GKW
 operator appears to have some sort of singularity associated with the point
 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset 

.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}f=g$
\end_inset 

 and substituting a Taylor's expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

, one finds 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{g^{(m)}(0)}{m!}=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{f^{(k)}(0)}{k!}\,(-)^{m}\;\frac{(k+m+1)!}{m!\,(k+1)!}\,\zeta(k+m+2)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The operator matrix elements can be immediately 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Mayer}

\end_inset 

 read off to be 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[U_{h}\right]_{mk}=(-1)^{m}\;\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+m+1\\
m\end{array}\right)\,\zeta(k+m+2)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where the factorials are replaced by the binomial coefficient that they
 form.
 Unfortunately, this is a poorly conditioned matrix, with a rapidly increasing
 matrix elements and a trace that does not converge.
 Progress may be made by applying a regulator and using Levin-type sequence
 acceleration techniques[ref].
 This leads to a number of curious identities, some of which were listed
 previously.
 However, the difficulty of working with divergent sums seems to outweigh
 any advantages given by the relatively simple form of the matrix elements.
 
\layout Standard

Presuming that there is some sort of singularity at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset 

, one may try expansions at different locations.
 Thus, consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}f^{(n)}(a)\,(x-a)^{n}/n!$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset 

 likewise expanded about 
\begin_inset Formula $x=b$
\end_inset 

.
 With this expansion, the operator relation 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}f=g$
\end_inset 

 becomes 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{g^{(m)}(b)}{m!}=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}U_{mn}^{(b,a)}\;\frac{f^{(n)}(a)}{n!}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Without much difficulty, one discovers that the matrix elements are given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
U_{mn}^{(b,a)}=(-1)^{m}\sum_{k=0}^{n}(-a)^{n-k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+m+1\\
m\end{array}\right)\,\zeta_{H}(k+m+2,1+b)\label{eq:general elts}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{H}(s,q)$
\end_inset 

 is the Hurwitz zeta function:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta_{H}(s,q)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{(n+q)^{s}}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $a=b=1/2$
\end_inset 

, one obtains the well-known expansion of 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Briggs}

\end_inset 

, which is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
U_{mn}^{(1/2,1/2)}=(-1)^{m}\sum_{k=0}^{n}\left(\frac{-1}{2}\right)^{n-k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+m+1\\
m\end{array}\right)\,\left[2^{m+k+2}\left(\zeta(k+m+2)-1\right)-\zeta(k+m+2)\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 
\layout Standard

A simpler expression is obtained by expanding about 
\begin_inset Formula $a=b=1$
\end_inset 

, and the matrix is rather well-conditioned and easier to work with.
 It is: 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
G_{mn}=\sum_{k=0}^{n}(-1)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+m+1\\
m\end{array}\right)\,\left[\zeta(k+m+2)-1\right]\label{eq:GKW-matrix-elts}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 which satisfies
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
(-)^{m}\frac{g^{(m)}(1)}{m!}=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}G_{mn}(-)^{n}\frac{f^{(n)}(1)}{n!}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The above will be the most convenient for expressing the Riemann zeta,
 and will be used in the next section.
 
\layout Standard

All of these expressions for the matrix elements for the GKW operator have
 a common form.
 It consists of two summations: the outer summation, and the summation defining
 the Hurwitz zeta function.
 Pulling out this second summation, one finds terms consisting of a series
 of polynomials, which are most simply expressed in terms of Gauss' hypergeometr
ic series: 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\Gamma_{mn}(x)\equiv(m+1)\,_{2}F_{1}\left[\begin{array}{c}
\begin{array}{cc}
-n\; & \; m+2\end{array}\\
2\end{array}\;;\; x\right]=\sum_{k=0}^{n}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+m+1\\
m\end{array}\right)(-x)^{k}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 These have a curious superficial resemblance to the shifted Legendre polynomial
 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\widetilde{P}_{n}(x)\equiv\sum_{k=0}^{n}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+n\\
n\end{array}\right)(-x)^{k}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

Switching the order of summation in equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:general elts}

\end_inset 

 gives the following: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
U_{mn}^{(b,a)}=(-1)^{m+n}a^{n}\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{(j+1+b)^{m+2}}\,_{2}F_{1}\left[\begin{array}{c}
\begin{array}{cc}
-n\; & \; m+2\end{array}\\
2\end{array}\;;\;\frac{-1}{a(j+1+b)}\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 
\layout Standard

Oddly, this appears to be in the form of a slightly generalized form of
 the GKW operator, the Ruelle-Mayer operator 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Mayer}

\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[U^{(s)}f\right](x)\equiv\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{(n+x)^{s}}f\left(\frac{1}{n+x}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset 

 is taken to be 
\begin_inset Formula $s=m+2$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f=_{2}F_{1}$
\end_inset 

.
 The general appearance and the matrix elements of the Ruelle-Mayer operator
 are only a slight variation of those for the GKW; and, for completeness,
 these are: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[U^{(s)}\right]_{mn}^{(b,a)}=(-1)^{m}\sum_{k=0}^{n}(-a)^{n-k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
m+k+s-1\\
m\end{array}\right)\,\zeta_{H}(m+k+s,1+b)\label{eq:RM-general elts}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The corresponding hypergeometric identity that comes into play is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{k=0}^{n}\left(-x\right)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
m+k+s-1\\
m\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
m+s-1\\
m\end{array}\right)\;_{2}F_{1}\left[\begin{array}{c}
\begin{array}{cc}
-n\; & \; m+s\end{array}\\
s\end{array}\;;\; x\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 
\layout Standard

As a final note, recall that the Hurwitz zeta may be expressed as the polygamma
 function for integer arguments, and that the polygamma functions are the
 chain of logarithmic derivatives of the gamma function.
 Thus, one may also expresses the matrix elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset 

 in the curious form 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
U_{mn}^{(b,a)}=\frac{(-a)^{n+1}}{m!}\sum_{k=0}^{n}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\frac{1}{a}\right)^{k+1}\frac{1}{(k+1)!}\,\frac{d^{k+1}}{dx^{k+1}}\psi^{(m)}(1+b)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

Here, the curious operator making an appearance is
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[P_{n,y}f\right](x)=\sum_{k=0}^{n}\left(-y\right)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\,\frac{f^{(k)}(x)}{k!}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{(k)}(x)$
\end_inset 

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

'th derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

.
 The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{n,y}$
\end_inset 

is upper-triangular, with all eigenvalues equal to 1, and all eigenvectors
