The Riemann Zeta and Stieltjes Constants
\layout Standard

Inserting the representation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:GKW-matrix-elts}

\end_inset 

 into the integral expression 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:Zeta as operator integral}

\end_inset 

 for the Riemann zeta gives 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta(s)=\frac{s}{s-1}-s\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{G_{mn}(-)^{n}}{(m+1)(m+2)}\left(\begin{array}{c}
s-1\\
n\end{array}\right)\label{eq:zeta-as-gkw}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 This expression may be considerably simplified.
 Several of the sums appearing in equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:zeta-as-gkw}

\end_inset 

 may be performed explicitly.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset 

to denote the intermediate sum, one may write
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta(s)=\frac{s}{s-1}-s\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}(-)^{n}\left(\begin{array}{c}
s-1\\
n\end{array}\right)t_{n}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 It is not too difficult to verify that the 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset 

 take the form
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
t_{n} & = & \sum_{m=0}^{\infty}\frac{G_{mn}}{(m+1)(m+2)}\nonumber \\
 & = & 1-\gamma+\sum_{k=1}^{n}(-)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left[\frac{1}{k}-\frac{\zeta(k+1)}{k+1}\right]\label{eq:t_n defn}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=0.577...$
\end_inset 

 is the Euler-Mascheroni Constant.
 For large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

, one finds that 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}\rightarrow1/2(n+1)$
\end_inset 

, motivating the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
a_{n}=t_{n}-\frac{1}{2(n+1)}\label{eq: a_n defn}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 so that the Riemann zeta may be written as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta(s)=\frac{s}{s-1}-\frac{1}{2}-s\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}(-)^{n}\left(\begin{array}{c}
s-1\\
n\end{array}\right)a_{n}\label{eq:zeta-as-a_n}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Writing the binomial coefficient as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{c}
s-1\\
n\end{array}\right)=(s-1)_{n}/n!$
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $(x)_{n}$
\end_inset 

 is the falling Pochhammer symbol, its clear that the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset 

 play the analogue of the Stieltjes constants for this kind of Umbral, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

divided differences
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 Newton-type equation.
 Unlike the Stieltjes constants, the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset 

 have a simple, finite expression.
 For example, the first few may be written as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
a_{0} & = & \frac{1}{2}-\gamma\label{eq:}\\
a_{1} & = & \frac{\zeta(2)}{2}-\gamma-\frac{1}{4}\\
a_{2} & = & \zeta(2)-\frac{\zeta(3)+2}{3}-\gamma\\
a_{3} & = & \frac{3}{2}\zeta(2)-\zeta(3)+\frac{\zeta(4)}{4}-\frac{23}{24}-\gamma\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 and so on.
 Numerically, the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset 

 are small, and seem to be bounded and oscillatory.
 A detailed numerical analysis of these values is given in the next section.
\layout Standard

Identities useful in the course of the manipulations needed to derive the
 above include 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
H_{n}=\sum_{m=1}^{n}\frac{1}{m}=-\sum_{k=1}^{n}\frac{(-1)^{k}}{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
-\sum_{k=0}^{n}\frac{(-x)^{k+1}}{k+1}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)=\frac{1-(1-x)^{n+1}}{n+1}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 This last identity is useful for partially resumming equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:t_n defn}

\end_inset 

 to improve convergence in numerical calculations.
 
\layout Standard

The 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset 

appear naturally in the Taylor's expansion for the Gamma function, and so
 one finds, with little difficulty, the generating function 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\alpha(z) & = & \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}a_{n}z^{n}\nonumber \\
 & = & \frac{1}{1-z}+\frac{\ln(1-z)}{z}\left(\frac{1}{1-z}-\frac{1}{2}\right)+\frac{1}{z}\ln\Gamma\left(\frac{1}{1-z}\right)\label{eq:alpha-exact}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 The above may be obtained by the straightforward application of equation
 6.1.33 from Abramowitz and Stegun 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{A&S}

\end_inset 

.
 This representation shows a complicated structure.
 There is a cut (from the logarithm) extending to the right for 
\begin_inset Formula $1<z$
\end_inset 

.
 In the cut there are poles (from the gamma function) at 
\begin_inset Formula $-n=1/(1-z)$
\end_inset 

, that is, at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1+1/n$
\end_inset 

, accumulating to at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset 

.
 There appears to be a simple zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=\infty$
\end_inset 

.
 The radius of convergence of the series involving the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset 

is one.
 As will be seen in the next section, the 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset 

 are oscillatory and exponentially decreasing, and so the sum at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset 

is convergent.
 One has:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}a_{n}=\ln\sqrt{2\pi}-1=-0.081061466795327...\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 which can be obtained from Sterling's asymptotic expansion for the gamma
 function, and 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}a_{n}2^{-n}=2-3\ln2=-0.079441541679836...\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

An exponential generating function is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}a_{n}\frac{z^{n}}{n!}=\frac{1}{2z}+e^{z}\left[1-\gamma-\mbox{Ein}(z)-\frac{1}{z}\left(\frac{1}{2}+\sum_{k=2}^{\infty}\frac{(-z)^{k}}{k!}\zeta(k)\right)\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ein}(z)$
\end_inset 

 is the entire exponential integral: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\mbox{Ein}(z)=-\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{k}\frac{(-z)^{k}}{k!}=e^{-z}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}H_{n}\frac{z^{n}}{n!}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{n}$
\end_inset 

 are the harmonic numbers.
\layout Standard

Its equally curious that other variations on the expression given in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:zeta-as-a_n}

\end_inset 

